<img class="size-full wp-image-1307828 aligncenter" src="https://i0.wp.com/www.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/NIMC.jpg?resize=640%2C336&#038;ssl=1" alt="NIMC adopts PPP in delivery of data capture" width="640" height="336" srcset="https://i0.wp.com/www.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/NIMC.jpg?w=764&amp;ssl=1 764w, https://i0.wp.com/www.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/NIMC.jpg?resize=300%2C157&amp;ssl=1 300w, https://i0.wp.com/www.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/NIMC.jpg?resize=58%2C30&amp;ssl=1 58w, https://i0.wp.com/www.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/NIMC.jpg?resize=260%2C136&amp;ssl=1 260w, https://i0.wp.com/www.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/NIMC.jpg?resize=200%2C105&amp;ssl=1 200w, https://i0.wp.com/www.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/NIMC.jpg?resize=560%2C294&amp;ssl=1 560w" sizes="(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px" data-recalc-dims="1" />The National Identity Management Commission has ordered the immediate shutdown of enrolment centres in Lagos, Katsina, Ekiti, Ogun and Anambra states as part of preventive measures against the spread of Coronavirus. The announcement was contained in a statement issued by the head of Corporate Communications of NIMC Mr Kayode Adegoke on Friday in Abuja. ” As part of the measures to stop the spread of the Coronavirus pandemic, the NIMC  has ordered the immediate shutdown of all its enrollment centers in Lagos, Katsina, Ekiti, Ogun and Anambra states,” he said. Adegoke said, the decision became necessary to protect  staff and applicants from  the Coronavirus. ”The move becomes necessary to prevent our Staff and applicants from getting more vulnerable to the pandemic. ” Consequently, all enrolment activities, card collection and other identity related activities are hereby suspended in the aforementioned states till further notice. ” The closure is not intended to create panic but to arrest the spread of the disease, which has become a global threat,” he said. He said, the commission however regretted any inconvenience caused as a result of their decision. ”We hereby regret any inconvenience the closure may  cause as our paramount concern as  responsible and responsive commission is the safety of all,” he said (NAN). Vanguard Seven years after its inception and with a huge amount of money already allocated to it by the federal government, the National Identity Management Commission is yet to meet its mandate of capturing all Nigerians on its database and issuing them with valid identity cards, clearly setting the stage for… December 16, 2017 In "News" The Nigeria Identity Card Management Commission (NIMC) has issued National Identity Number (NIN) to no fewer than 30 million Nigerians. March 4, 2018 In "News" The National Identity Management Commission (NIMC) insists that only people who posses a form of identification as Nigerians will be enrolled into the National Identity Number (NIN) project. November 10, 2012 In "News"